# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: generalized-linear-models
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] In probability and statistics, an **exponential family** is a parametric set of probability distributions of a certain form, specified below.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] The term **exponential class** is sometimes used in place of "exponential family", or the older term **Koopman–Darmois family**.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] Sometimes loosely referred to as *the* exponential family, this class of distributions is distinct because they all possess a variety of desirable properties, most importantly the existence of a sufficient statistic.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] The concept of exponential families is credited to E.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] Exponential families of distributions provide a general framework for selecting a possible alternative parameterisation of a parametric family of distributions, in terms of natural parameters, and for defining useful sample statistics, called the natural sufficient statistics of the family.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] Most of the commonly used distributions form an exponential family or subset of an exponential family, listed in the subsection below.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] The subsections following it are a sequence of increasingly more general mathematical definitions of an exponential family.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] A casual reader may wish to restrict attention to the first and simplest definition, which corresponds to a single-parameter family of discrete or continuous probability distributions.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] Exponential families include many of the most common distributions.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] A number of common distributions are exponential families, but only when certain parameters are fixed and known.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] Note that in each case, the parameters which must be fixed are those that set a limit on the range of values that can possibly be observed.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] Examples of common distributions that are *not* exponential families are Student's *t*, most mixture distributions, and even the family of uniform distributions when the bounds are not fixed.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] See the section below on examples for more discussion.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] The value of $\theta$ is called the *parameter* of the family.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] The function *h*(*x*) must be non-negative.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] Often x is a vector of measurements, in which case $T(x)$ may be a function from the space of possible values of x to the real numbers.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] More generally, $\eta (\theta )$ and $T(x)$ can each be vector-valued such that $\eta (\theta )\cdot T(x)$ is real-valued.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] However, see the discussion below on vector parameters, regarding the *curved* exponential family.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] If $\eta (\theta )=\theta \ ,$ then the exponential family is said to be in *canonical form*.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] By defining a transformed parameter $\eta =\eta (\theta )\ ,$ it is always possible to convert an exponential family to canonical form.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] The canonical form is non-unique, since $\eta (\theta )$ can be multiplied by any nonzero constant, provided that *T*(*x*) is multiplied by that constant's reciprocal, or a constant *c* can be added to $\eta (\theta )$ and *h*(*x*) multiplied by $\exp \left[{-c}\cdot T(x)\,\right]$ to offset it.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] In the special case that $\eta (\theta )=\theta$ and *T*(*x*) = *x*, then the family is called a *natural exponential family*.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] Even when x is a scalar, and there is only a single parameter, the functions $\eta (\theta )$ and $T(x)$ can still be vectors, as described below.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] The function $A(\theta )\ ,$ or equivalently $g(\theta )\ ,$ is automatically determined once the other functions have been chosen, since it must assume a form that causes the distribution to be normalized (sum or integrate to one over the entire domain).
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] Furthermore, both of these functions can always be written as functions of $\eta \ ,$ even when $\eta (\theta )$ is not a one-to-one function, i.e. two or more different values of $\theta$ map to the same value of $\eta (\theta )\ ,$ and hence $\eta (\theta )$ cannot be inverted.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] There are further restrictions on how many such factors can occur.
