[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] and hence factorizes inside of the exponent.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] and again factorizes inside of the exponent.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] This form writes the sum as a dot product of vector-valued functions ${\boldsymbol {\eta }}({\boldsymbol {\theta }})$ and *T*(*x*).
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] That is, if the *dimension*, d, of the parameter vector is less than the *number of functions*, s, of the parameter vector in the above representation of the probability density function.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] Most common distributions in the exponential family are *not* curved, and many algorithms designed to work with any exponential family implicitly or explicitly assume that the distribution is not curved.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] Just as in the case of a scalar-valued parameter, the function $A({\boldsymbol {\theta }})$ or equivalently $g({\boldsymbol {\theta }})$ is automatically determined by the normalization constraint, once the other functions have been chosen.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] Even if ${\boldsymbol {\eta }}({\boldsymbol {\theta }})$ is not one-to-one, functions $A({\boldsymbol {\eta }})$ and $g({\boldsymbol {\eta }})$ can be defined by requiring that the distribution is normalized for each value of the natural parameter ${\boldsymbol {\eta }}$ .
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] The above forms may sometimes be seen with ${\boldsymbol {\eta }}^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {T} (x)$ in place of ${\boldsymbol {\eta }}\cdot \mathbf {T} (x)\,$ .
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] These are exactly equivalent formulations, merely using different notation for the dot product.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] The vector-parameter form over a single scalar-valued random variable can be trivially expanded to cover a joint distribution over a vector of random variables.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] The dimensions k of the random variable need not match the dimension d of the parameter vector, nor (in the case of a curved exponential function) the dimension s of the natural parameter ${\boldsymbol {\eta }}$ and sufficient statistic **T**(**x**) .
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] We use cumulative distribution functions (CDF) in order to encompass both discrete and continuous distributions.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] Suppose H is a non-decreasing function of a real variable.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] Then Lebesgue–Stieltjes integrals with respect to $dH(\mathbf {x} )$ are integrals with respect to the *reference measure* of the exponential family generated by H .
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] In the definitions above, the functions *T*(*x*), *η*(*θ*), and *A*(*η*) were arbitrary.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] However, these functions have important interpretations in the resulting probability distribution.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] The function A is important in its own right, because the mean, variance and other moments of the sufficient statistic *T*(*x*) can be derived simply by differentiating *A*(*η*).
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] For example, because log(*x*) is one of the components of the sufficient statistic of the gamma distribution, $\operatorname {\mathcal {E}} [\log x]$ can be easily determined for this distribution using *A*(*η*).
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] Technically, this is true because $K{\left(u\mid \eta \right)}=A(\eta +u)-A(\eta )\,,$ is the cumulant generating function of the sufficient statistic.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] Exponential families have a large number of properties that make them extremely useful for statistical analysis.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] In many cases, it can be shown that *only* exponential families have these properties.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] Given an exponential family defined by $f_{X}{\!(x\mid \theta )}=h(x)\exp \left[\theta \cdot T(x)-A(\theta )\right]$ , where $\Theta$ is the parameter space, such that $\theta \in \Theta \subset \mathbb {R} ^{k}$ .
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] The normal, exponential, log-normal, gamma, chi-squared, beta, Dirichlet, Bernoulli, categorical, Poisson, geometric, inverse Gaussian, ALAAM, von Mises, and von Mises-Fisher distributions are all exponential families.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] Some distributions are exponential families only if some of their parameters are held fixed.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] The family of Pareto distributions with a fixed minimum bound *x*m form an exponential family.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] The families of binomial and multinomial distributions with fixed number of trials *n* but unknown probability parameter(s) are exponential families.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] The family of negative binomial distributions with fixed number of failures (a.k.a. stopping-time parameter) *r* is an exponential family.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] However, when any of the above-mentioned fixed parameters are allowed to vary, the resulting family is not an exponential family.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] As mentioned above, as a general rule, the support of an exponential family must remain the same across all parameter settings in the family.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] This is why the above cases (e.g. binomial with varying number of trials, Pareto with varying minimum bound) are not exponential families — in all of the cases, the parameter in question affects the support (particularly, changing the minimum or maximum possible value).
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] For similar reasons, neither the discrete uniform distribution nor continuous uniform distribution are exponential families as one or both bounds vary.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] The Weibull distribution with fixed shape parameter *k* is an exponential family.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] Unlike in the previous examples, the shape parameter does not affect the support; the fact that allowing it to vary makes the Weibull non-exponential is due rather to the particular form of the Weibull's probability density function (*k* appears in the exponent of an exponent).
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] In general, distributions that result from a finite or infinite mixture of other distributions, e.g. mixture model densities and compound probability distributions, are *not* exponential families.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] Other examples of distributions that are not exponential families are the F-distribution, Cauchy distribution, hypergeometric distribution and logistic distribution.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] Following are some detailed examples of the representation of some useful distribution as exponential families.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] As a first example, consider a random variable distributed normally with unknown mean μ and *known* variance *σ*2.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] If *σ* = 1 this is in canonical form, as then *η*(*μ*) = *μ*.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] Next, consider the case of a normal distribution with unknown mean and unknown variance.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] As an example of a discrete exponential family, consider the binomial distribution with *known* number of trials n.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] The following table shows how to rewrite a number of common distributions as exponential-family distributions with natural parameters.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] Refer to the flashcards for main exponential families.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] The above formulas choose the functional form of the exponential-family with a log-partition function $A({\boldsymbol {\eta }})$ .
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] The reason for this is so that the moments of the sufficient statistics can be calculated easily, simply by differentiating this function.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] Alternative forms involve either parameterizing this function in terms of the normal parameter ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ instead of the natural parameter, and/or using a factor $g({\boldsymbol {\eta }})$ outside of the exponential.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] Thus, there are only $k-1$ independent parameters.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] Variants 1 and 2 are not actually standard exponential families at all.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] Rather they are *curved exponential families*, i.e. there are $k-1$ independent parameters embedded in a k -dimensional parameter space.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] Many of the standard results for exponential families do not apply to curved exponential families.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] An example is the log-partition function $A(x)$ , which has the value of 0 in the curved cases.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] In standard exponential families, the derivatives of this function correspond to the moments (more technically, the cumulants) of the sufficient statistics, e.g. the mean and variance.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p01] However, a value of 0 suggests that the mean and variance of all the sufficient statistics are uniformly 0, whereas in fact the mean of the i th sufficient statistic should be $p_{i}$ .
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] We start with the normalization of the probability distribution.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] In general, any non-negative function *f*(*x*) that serves as the kernel of a probability distribution (the part encoding all dependence on *x*) can be made into a proper distribution by normalizing: i.e.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] The factor *Z* is sometimes termed the *normalizer* or *partition function*, based on an analogy to statistical physics.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] This justifies calling *A* the *log-normalizer* or *log-partition function*.
