[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] An important subclass of exponential families are the natural exponential families, which have a similar form for the moment-generating function for the distribution of x.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] The first two raw moments and all mixed second moments can be recovered from these two identities.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] Higher-order moments and cumulants are obtained by higher derivatives.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] This technique is often useful when *T* is a complicated function of the data, whose moments are difficult to calculate by integration.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] Another way to see this that does not rely on the theory of cumulants is to begin from the fact that the distribution of an exponential family must be normalized, and differentiate.
