[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] Both of these expectations are needed when deriving the variational Bayes update equations in a Bayes network involving a Wishart distribution (which is the conjugate prior of the multivariate normal distribution).
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] Computing these formulas using integration would be much more difficult.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] The first one, for example, would require matrix integration.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] The relative entropy (Kullback–Leibler divergence, KL divergence) of two distributions in an exponential family has a simple expression as the Bregman divergence between the natural parameters with respect to the log-normalizer.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] The relative entropy is defined in terms of an integral, while the Bregman divergence is defined in terms of a derivative and inner product, and thus is easier to calculate and has a closed-form expression (assuming the derivative has a closed-form expression).
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] Further, the Bregman divergence in terms of the natural parameters and the log-normalizer equals the Bregman divergence of the dual parameters (expectation parameters), in the opposite order, for the convex conjugate function.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] Exponential families arise naturally as the answer to the following question: what is the maximum-entropy distribution consistent with given constraints on expected values?
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] The information entropy of a probability distribution *dF*(*x*) can only be computed with respect to some other probability distribution (or, more generally, a positive measure), and both measures must be mutually absolutely continuous.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] Accordingly, we need to pick a *reference measure* *dH*(*x*) with the same support as *dF*(*x*).
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] where *dF*/*dH* and *dH*/*dF* are Radon–Nikodym derivatives.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] Consider now a collection of observable quantities (random variables) *Ti*.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] The probability distribution *dF* whose entropy with respect to *dH* is greatest, subject to the conditions that the expected value of *T**i* be equal to *ti*, is an exponential family with *dH* as reference measure and (*T*1, ..., *Tn*) as sufficient statistic.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] The derivation is a simple variational calculation using Lagrange multipliers.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] Normalization is imposed by letting *T*0 = 1 be one of the constraints.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] The natural parameters of the distribution are the Lagrange multipliers, and the normalization factor is the Lagrange multiplier associated to *T*0.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] For examples of such derivations, see Maximum entropy probability distribution.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] According to the **Pitman–Koopman–Darmois theorem**, among families of probability distributions whose domain does not vary with the parameter being estimated, only in exponential families is there a sufficient statistic whose dimension remains bounded as sample size increases.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] *n*) are independent, identically distributed random variables.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] Exponential families are also important in Bayesian statistics.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] In Bayesian statistics a prior distribution is multiplied by a likelihood function and then normalised to produce a posterior distribution.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] In the case of a likelihood which belongs to an exponential family there exists a conjugate prior, which is often also in an exponential family.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] A conjugate prior is one which, when combined with the likelihood and normalised, produces a posterior distribution which is of the same type as the prior.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] For example, if one is estimating the success probability of a binomial distribution, then if one chooses to use a beta distribution as one's prior, the posterior is another beta distribution.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] This makes the computation of the posterior particularly simple.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] Similarly, if one is estimating the parameter of a Poisson distribution the use of a gamma prior will lead to another gamma posterior.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] Conjugate priors are often very flexible and can be very convenient.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] However, if one's belief about the likely value of the theta parameter of a binomial is represented by (say) a bimodal (two-humped) prior distribution, then this cannot be represented by a beta distribution.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] It can however be represented by using a mixture density as the prior, here a combination of two beta distributions; this is a form of hyperprior.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] An arbitrary likelihood will not belong to an exponential family, and thus in general no conjugate prior exists.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] The posterior will then have to be computed by numerical methods.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] To show that the above prior distribution is a conjugate prior, we can derive the posterior.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] The last line is the kernel of the posterior distribution, i.e.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] This shows that the posterior has the same form as the prior.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] which is termed the sufficient statistic of the data.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] That is, the value of the sufficient statistic is sufficient to completely determine the posterior distribution.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] The actual data points themselves are not needed, and all sets of data points with the same sufficient statistic will have the same distribution.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] This is important because the dimension of the sufficient statistic does not grow with the data size — it has only as many components as the components of ${\boldsymbol {\eta }}$ (equivalently, the number of parameters of the distribution of a single data point).
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] This shows that the update equations can be written simply in terms of the number of data points and the sufficient statistic of the data.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] This can be seen clearly in the various examples of update equations shown in the conjugate prior page.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] Because of the way that the sufficient statistic is computed, it necessarily involves sums of components of the data (in some cases disguised as products or other forms — a product can be written in terms of a sum of logarithms).
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] If the likelihood $z|\eta \sim e^{\eta z}f_{1}(\eta )f_{0}(z)$ is an exponential family, then the unbiased estimator of $\eta$ is $-{\frac {d}{dz}}\ln f_{0}(z)$ .
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] A one-parameter exponential family has a monotone non-decreasing likelihood ratio in the sufficient statistic *T*(*x*), provided that *η*(*θ*) is non-decreasing.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] As a consequence, there exists a uniformly most powerful test for testing the hypothesis *H*0: *θ* ≥ *θ*0 *vs*.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] Exponential families form the basis for the distribution functions used in generalized linear models (GLM), a class of model that encompasses many of the commonly used regression models in statistics.
[src:generalized-linear-models/exponential-family-p02] Examples include logistic regression using the binomial family and Poisson regression.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] In statistics, a **generalized linear model** (**GLM**) is a flexible generalization of ordinary linear regression.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] The GLM generalizes linear regression by allowing the linear model to be related to the response variable via a *link function* and by allowing the magnitude of the variance of each measurement to be a function of its predicted value.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] Generalized linear models were formulated by John Nelder and Robert Wedderburn as a way of unifying various other statistical models, including linear regression, logistic regression and Poisson regression.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] They proposed an iteratively reweighted least squares method for maximum likelihood estimation (MLE) of the model parameters.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] MLE remains popular and is the default method on many statistical computing packages.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] Other approaches, including Bayesian regression and least squares fitting to variance stabilized responses, have been developed.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] Ordinary linear regression predicts the expected value of a given unknown quantity (the *response variable*, a random variable) as a linear combination of a set of observed values (*predictors*).
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] This implies that a constant change in a predictor leads to a constant change in the response variable (i.e. a *linear-response model*).
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] This is appropriate when the response variable can vary, to a good approximation, indefinitely in either direction, or more generally for any quantity that only varies by a relatively small amount compared to the variation in the predictive variables, e.g. human heights.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] However, these assumptions are inappropriate for some types of response variables.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] For example, in cases where the response variable is expected to be always positive and varying over a wide range, constant input changes lead to geometrically (i.e. exponentially) varying, rather than constantly varying, output changes.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] As an example, suppose a linear prediction model learns from some data (perhaps primarily drawn from large beaches) that a 10 degree temperature decrease would lead to 1,000 fewer people visiting the beach.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] This model is unlikely to generalize well over differently-sized beaches.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] More specifically, the problem is that if the model is used to predict the new attendance with a temperature drop of 10 for a beach that regularly receives 50 beachgoers, it would predict an impossible attendance value of −950.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] Logically, a more realistic model would instead predict a constant *rate* of increased beach attendance (e.g. an increase of 10 degrees leads to a doubling in beach attendance, and a drop of 10 degrees leads to a halving in attendance).
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] Such a model is termed an *exponential-response model* (or *log-linear model*, since the logarithm of the response is predicted to vary linearly).
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] Similarly, a model that predicts a probability of making a yes/no choice (a Bernoulli variable) is even less suitable as a linear-response model, since probabilities are bounded on both ends (they must be between 0 and 1).
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] Imagine, for example, a model that predicts the likelihood of a given person going to the beach as a function of temperature.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] A reasonable model might predict, for example, that a change in 10 degrees makes a person two times more or less likely to go to the beach.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] But what does "twice as likely" mean in terms of a probability?
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] It cannot literally mean to double the probability value (e.g.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] Rather, it is the *odds* that are doubling: from 2:1 odds, to 4:1 odds, to 8:1 odds, etc.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] Such a model is a *log-odds or logistic model*.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] In a generalized linear model (GLM), each outcome **Y** of the dependent variables is assumed to be generated from a particular distribution in an exponential family, a large class of probability distributions that includes the normal, binomial, Poisson and gamma distributions, among others.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] where E(**Y** | **X**) is the expected value of **Y** conditional on **X**; **X*β*** is the *linear predictor*, a linear combination of unknown parameters ***β***; *g* is the link function.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] It is convenient if **V** follows from an exponential family of distributions, but it may simply be that the variance is a function of the predicted value.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] The unknown parameters, ***β***, are typically estimated with maximum likelihood, maximum quasi-likelihood, or Bayesian techniques.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] The *dispersion parameter*, $\tau$ , typically is known and is usually related to the variance of the distribution.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] Many common distributions are in this family, including the normal, exponential, gamma, Poisson, Bernoulli, and (for fixed number of trials) binomial, multinomial, and negative binomial.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ is related to the mean of the distribution.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] Original formulation by John Nelder and Robert Wedderburn sets $T(y)=y$ , which is a key requirement for having unbiased estimating equations for $\theta$ that yields many attractive properties, including consistency of maximum likelihood estimate under distributional misspecification.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] If $\mathbf {b} ({\boldsymbol {\theta }})$ is the identity function, then the distribution is said to be in canonical form (or *natural form*).
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] Note that any distribution can be converted to canonical form by rewriting ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ as ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}'$ and then applying the transformation ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}=\mathbf {b} ({\boldsymbol {\theta }}')$ .
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] It is always possible to convert $A({\boldsymbol {\theta }})$ in terms of the new parametrization, even if $\mathbf {b} ({\boldsymbol {\theta }}')$ is not a one-to-one function; see comments in the page on exponential families.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] The linear predictor is the quantity which incorporates the information about the independent variables into the model.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] The symbol *η* (Greek "eta") denotes a linear predictor.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] It is related to the expected value of the data through the link function.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] The link function provides the relationship between the linear predictor and the mean of the distribution function.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] There are many commonly used link functions, and their choice is informed by several considerations.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] There is always a well-defined *canonical* link function which is derived from the exponential of the response's density function.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] However, in some cases it makes sense to try to match the domain of the link function to the range of the distribution function's mean, or use a non-canonical link function for algorithmic purposes, for example Bayesian probit regression.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] When using the canonical link function, $g(\mu )=\theta =\mathbf {X} {\boldsymbol {\beta }},$ which allows $\mathbf {X} ^{\rm {T}}\mathbf {Y}$ to be a sufficient statistic for ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}$ .
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] Following is a table of several exponential-family distributions in common use and the data they are typically used for, along with the canonical link functions and their inverses (sometimes referred to as the mean function, as done here).
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] In the cases of the exponential and gamma distributions, the domain of the canonical link function is not the same as the permitted range of the mean.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] In particular, the linear predictor may be positive, which would give an impossible negative mean.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] When maximizing the likelihood, precautions must be taken to avoid this.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] An alternative is to use a noncanonical link function.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] In the case of the Bernoulli, binomial, categorical and multinomial distributions, the support of the distributions is not the same type of data as the parameter being predicted.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] In all of these cases, the predicted parameter is one or more probabilities, i.e. real numbers in the range $[0,1]$ .
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] The resulting model is known as *logistic regression* (or *multinomial logistic regression* in the case that *K*-way rather than binary values are being predicted).
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] For the Bernoulli and binomial distributions, the parameter is a single probability, indicating the likelihood of occurrence of a single event.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] The Bernoulli still satisfies the basic condition of the generalized linear model in that, even though a single outcome will always be either 0 or 1, the *expected value* will nonetheless be a real-valued probability, i.e. the probability of occurrence of a "yes" (or 1) outcome.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] Similarly, in a binomial distribution, the expected value is *Np*, i.e. the expected proportion of "yes" outcomes will be the probability to be predicted.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] For categorical and multinomial distributions, the parameter to be predicted is a *K*-vector of probabilities, with the further restriction that all probabilities must add up to 1.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] Each probability indicates the likelihood of occurrence of one of the *K* possible values.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] For the multinomial distribution, and for the vector form of the categorical distribution, the expected values of the elements of the vector can be related to the predicted probabilities similarly to the binomial and Bernoulli distributions.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] where ${\mathcal {I}}({\boldsymbol {\beta }}^{(t)})$ is the Fisher information matrix.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] Note that if the canonical link function is used, then they are the same.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] In general, the posterior distribution cannot be found in closed form and so must be approximated, usually using Laplace approximations or some type of Markov chain Monte Carlo method such as Gibbs sampling.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] A possible point of confusion has to do with the distinction between generalized linear models and general linear models, two broad statistical models.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] Co-originator John Nelder has expressed regret over this terminology.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] The general linear model may be viewed as a special case of the generalized linear model with identity link and responses normally distributed.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] As most exact results of interest are obtained only for the general linear model, the general linear model has undergone a somewhat longer historical development.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] Results for the generalized linear model with non-identity link are asymptotic (tending to work well with large samples).
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] A simple, very important example of a generalized linear model (also an example of a general linear model) is linear regression.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] In linear regression, the use of the least-squares estimator is justified by the Gauss–Markov theorem, which does not assume that the distribution is normal.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] From the perspective of generalized linear models, however, it is useful to suppose that the distribution function is the normal distribution with constant variance and the link function is the identity, which is the canonical link if the variance is known.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] Under these assumptions, the least-squares estimator is obtained as the maximum-likelihood parameter estimate.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] For the normal distribution, the generalized linear model has a closed form expression for the maximum-likelihood estimates, which is convenient.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] Most other GLMs lack closed form estimates.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] When the response data, *Y*, are binary (taking on only values 0 and 1), the distribution function is generally chosen to be the Bernoulli distribution and the interpretation of *μ*i is then the probability, *p*, of *Y*i taking on the value one.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] There are several popular link functions for binomial functions.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] GLMs with this setup are logistic regression models (or *logit models*).
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] Alternatively, the inverse of any continuous cumulative distribution function (CDF) can be used for the link since the CDF's range is $[0,1]$ , the range of the binomial mean.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] The normal CDF $\Phi$ is a popular choice and yields the probit model.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] This link function is asymmetric and will often produce different results from the logit and probit link functions.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] The cloglog model corresponds to applications where we observe either zero events (e.g., defects) or one or more, where the number of events is assumed to follow the Poisson distribution.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] where *μ* is a positive number denoting the expected number of events.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] A linear model requires the response variable to take values over the entire real line.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] Since *μ* must be positive, we can enforce that by taking the logarithm, and letting log(*μ*) be a linear model.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] The identity link *g(p) = p* is also sometimes used for binomial data to yield a linear probability model.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] However, the identity link can predict nonsense "probabilities" less than zero or greater than one.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] This can be avoided by using a transformation like cloglog, probit or logit (or any inverse cumulative distribution function).
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] A primary merit of the identity link is that it can be estimated using linear math—and other standard link functions are approximately linear matching the identity link near *p* = 0.5.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] where the dispersion parameter *τ* is exactly 1 for the binomial distribution.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] Indeed, the standard binomial likelihood omits *τ*.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] When it is present, the model is called "quasibinomial", and the modified likelihood is called a quasi-likelihood, since it is not generally the likelihood corresponding to any real family of probability distributions.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] If *τ* exceeds 1, the model is said to exhibit overdispersion.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] The binomial case may be easily extended to allow for a multinomial distribution as the response (also, a Generalized Linear Model for counts, with a constrained total).
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] Different links *g* lead to ordinal regression models like proportional odds models or ordered probit models.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] Different links *g* lead to multinomial logit or multinomial probit models.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] These are more general than the ordered response models, and more parameters are estimated.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] Another example of generalized linear models includes Poisson regression which models count data using the Poisson distribution.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] The link is typically the logarithm, the canonical link.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] where the dispersion parameter *τ* is typically fixed at exactly one.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] When it is not, the resulting quasi-likelihood model is often described as Poisson with overdispersion or *quasi-Poisson*.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] It is related to fractional regression models based on quasi-maximum likelihood if the variance function is chosen differently.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] The standard GLM assumes that the observations are uncorrelated.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] The smoothing functions *fi* are estimated from the data.
[src:generalized-linear-models/generalized-linear-model] In general this requires a large number of data points and is computationally intensive.
[src:generalized-linear-models/iteratively-reweighted-least-squares] One of the advantages of IRLS over linear programming and convex programming is that it can be used with Gauss–Newton and Levenberg–Marquardt numerical algorithms.
[src:generalized-linear-models/iteratively-reweighted-least-squares] IRLS can be used for ***ℓ*1** minimization and smoothed ***ℓ*p** minimization, *p* < 1, in compressed sensing problems.
[src:generalized-linear-models/iteratively-reweighted-least-squares] It has been proved that the algorithm has a linear rate of convergence for *ℓ*1 norm and superlinear for *ℓ**t* with *t* < 1, under the restricted isometry property, which is generally a sufficient condition for sparse solutions.
[src:generalized-linear-models/iteratively-reweighted-least-squares] To avoid dividing by zero, regularization must be done, so in practice the formula is $w_{i}^{(t)}={\frac {1}{\max \left\{\delta ,\left|y_{i}-X_{i}{\boldsymbol {\beta }}^{(t)}\right|\right\}}}.$ where $\delta$ is some small value, like 0.0001.
[src:generalized-linear-models/iteratively-reweighted-least-squares] Note the use of $\delta$ in the weighting function is equivalent to the Huber loss function in robust estimation.
[src:generalized-linear-models/nuisance-parameter] In statistics, a **nuisance parameter** is any parameter which is unspecified but which must be accounted for in the hypothesis testing of the parameters which are of interest.
[src:generalized-linear-models/nuisance-parameter] The classic example of a nuisance parameter comes from the normal distribution, a member of the location–scale family.
[src:generalized-linear-models/nuisance-parameter] In the case of normal distribution, the variance(s), *σ2* is often not specified or known, but one desires to hypothesis test on the mean(s).
[src:generalized-linear-models/nuisance-parameter] Nuisance parameters are often scale parameters, but not always; for example in errors-in-variables models, the unknown true location of each observation is a nuisance parameter.
[src:generalized-linear-models/nuisance-parameter] A parameter may also cease to be a "nuisance" if it becomes the object of study, is estimated from data, or known.
[src:generalized-linear-models/nuisance-parameter] The general treatment of nuisance parameters can be broadly similar between frequentist and Bayesian approaches to theoretical statistics.
[src:generalized-linear-models/nuisance-parameter] It relies on an attempt to partition the likelihood function into components representing information about the parameters of interest and information about the other (nuisance) parameters.
[src:generalized-linear-models/nuisance-parameter] This can involve ideas about sufficient statistics and ancillary statistics.
[src:generalized-linear-models/nuisance-parameter] When this partition can be achieved it may be possible to complete a Bayesian analysis for the parameters of interest by determining their joint posterior distribution algebraically.
[src:generalized-linear-models/nuisance-parameter] The partition allows frequentist theory to develop general estimation approaches in the presence of nuisance parameters.
[src:generalized-linear-models/nuisance-parameter] If the partition cannot be achieved it may still be possible to make use of an approximate partition.
[src:generalized-linear-models/nuisance-parameter] In some special cases, it is possible to formulate methods that circumvent the presences of nuisance parameters.
[src:generalized-linear-models/nuisance-parameter] The t-test provides a practically useful test because the test statistic does not depend on the unknown variance but only the sample variance.
[src:generalized-linear-models/nuisance-parameter] It is a case where use can be made of a pivotal quantity.
[src:generalized-linear-models/nuisance-parameter] However, in other cases no such circumvention is known.
[src:generalized-linear-models/nuisance-parameter] Practical approaches to statistical analysis treat nuisance parameters somewhat differently in frequentist and Bayesian methodologies.
[src:generalized-linear-models/nuisance-parameter] A general approach in a frequentist analysis can be based on maximum likelihood-ratio tests.
[src:generalized-linear-models/nuisance-parameter] These provide both significance tests and confidence intervals for the parameters of interest which are approximately valid for moderate to large sample sizes and which take account of the presence of nuisance parameters.
[src:generalized-linear-models/nuisance-parameter] See Basu (1977) for some general discussion and Spall and Garner (1990) for some discussion relative to the identification of parameters in linear dynamic (i.e., state space representation) models.
[src:generalized-linear-models/nuisance-parameter] In Bayesian analysis, a generally applicable approach creates random samples from the joint posterior distribution of all the parameters: see Markov chain Monte Carlo.
[src:generalized-linear-models/nuisance-parameter] Given these, the joint distribution of only the parameters of interest can be readily found by marginalizing over the nuisance parameters.
[src:generalized-linear-models/nuisance-parameter] However, this approach may not always be computationally efficient if some or all of the nuisance parameters can be eliminated on a theoretical basis.
[src:generalized-linear-models/quasi-likelihood] In statistics, **quasi-likelihood** methods are used to estimate parameters in a statistical model when exact likelihood methods, for example maximum likelihood estimation, are computationally infeasible.
[src:generalized-linear-models/quasi-likelihood] Due to the wrong likelihood being used, quasi-likelihood estimators lose asymptotic efficiency compared to, e.g., maximum likelihood estimators.
[src:generalized-linear-models/quasi-likelihood] Under broadly applicable conditions, quasi-likelihood estimators are consistent and asymptotically normal.
[src:generalized-linear-models/quasi-likelihood] The asymptotic covariance matrix can be obtained using the so-called *sandwich estimator*.
[src:generalized-linear-models/quasi-likelihood] Examples of quasi-likelihood methods include the generalized estimating equations and pairwise likelihood approaches.
[src:generalized-linear-models/quasi-likelihood] The term **quasi-likelihood function** was introduced by Robert Wedderburn in 1974 to describe a function that has similar properties to the log-likelihood function but is not the log-likelihood corresponding to any actual probability distribution.
[src:generalized-linear-models/quasi-likelihood] He proposed to fit certain quasi-likelihood models using a straightforward extension of the algorithms used to fit generalized linear models.
[src:generalized-linear-models/quasi-likelihood] Quasi-likelihood estimation is one way of allowing for overdispersion, that is, greater variability in the data than would be expected from the statistical model used.
[src:generalized-linear-models/quasi-likelihood] It is most often used with models for count data or grouped binary data, i.e. data that would otherwise be modelled using the Poisson or binomial distribution.
[src:generalized-linear-models/quasi-likelihood] Instead of specifying a probability distribution for the data, only a relationship between the mean and the variance is specified in the form of a variance function giving the variance as a function of the mean.
[src:generalized-linear-models/quasi-likelihood] Generally, this function is allowed to include a multiplicative factor known as the **overdispersion parameter** or **scale parameter** that is estimated from the data.
[src:generalized-linear-models/quasi-likelihood] Most commonly, the variance function is of a form such that fixing the overdispersion parameter at unity results in the variance-mean relationship of an actual probability distribution such as the binomial or Poisson.
[src:generalized-linear-models/quasi-likelihood] Random-effects models, and more generally mixed models (hierarchical models) provide an alternative method of fitting data exhibiting overdispersion using fully specified probability models.
[src:generalized-linear-models/quasi-likelihood] However, these methods often become complex and computationally intensive to fit to binary or count data.
[src:generalized-linear-models/quasi-likelihood] Quasi-likelihood methods have the advantage of relative computational simplicity, speed and robustness, as they can make use of the more straightforward algorithms developed to fit generalized linear models.
